Let's start with life sciences.

19:17.690 --> 19:23.295 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Life sciences is
the largest
of the five topics for
recipients.

19:23.329 --> 19:30.736 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Each person or awardee group
gets a $3 million
prize for major contributions to
the understanding

19:30.770 --> 19:32.638 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of the inner workings of life.

19:32.671 --> 19:36.876 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, for example, Stephen
Elledge, a scientist
at Harvard and he's affiliated
with the Howard

19:36.909 --> 19:44.183 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Hughes Medical Institute as
well, was recognized
for his research into how DNA
detects when

19:44.216 --> 19:45.418 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
it is damaged.

19:45.451 --> 19:47.253 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Here he is explaining it.

19:47.286 --> 19:50.256 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEPHEN ELLEDGE, Harvard Medical
School: DNA
has this incredible ability to
sense its own

19:50.289 --> 19:51.323 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
integrity.

19:51.357 --> 19:54.360 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's a molecule, but it knows
when it's damaged.

19:54.393 --> 20:00.066 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it has built a signaling
apparatus that's
a little bit like sort of a
radio station.

20:00.099 --> 20:05.471 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It sends out signals when
there's a problem
and calls in the troops and it
organizes everything.

20:05.504 --> 20:08.140 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
So it's really about
communication inside
the cell.

20:08.174 --> 20:13.946 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: This is key
because disruptions
of this mechanism are linked to
cancer, and

20:13.979 --> 20:17.917 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
there are already some cancer
treatments being
implemented that are based on
this research.

20:17.950 --> 20:19.819 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So it's very exciting, Hari.

20:19.852 --> 20:22.955 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right,
there was a special
category -- award in the
category of physics.

20:22.988 --> 20:24.090 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Tell us about it.

20:24.123 --> 20:26.225 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Yes, physics is
always interesting.

20:26.258 --> 20:29.895 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There were some awards which got
into string
theory, which would be too hard
to explain

20:29.929 --> 20:30.896 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in the time we have.

20:30.930 --> 20:32.631 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
But this one is very
interesting.

20:32.665 --> 20:38.737 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And you have about it, the Laser
Interferometer
Gravitational-Wave Observatory,
or LIGO.

20:38.771 --> 20:41.707 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It earned a special prize in
fundamental physics.

20:41.741 --> 20:43.442 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
What is LIGO?

20:43.476 --> 20:48.013 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, this 1,000-plus-member
team will be
splitting that $3 million prize
for their

20:48.047 --> 20:53.385 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
detection of gravity waves
caused by the merging
two of black holes.

20:53.419 --> 20:58.924 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LIGO uses lasers to precisely
measure the
position of mirrors separated
from each other

20:58.958 --> 21:00.693 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
by about 2.5 miles.

21:00.726 --> 21:06.065 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, in addition, it takes these
measurements
at two locations about 1,900
miles apart,

21:06.098 --> 21:08.934 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
one in Louisiana, one in the
state of Washington.

21:08.968 --> 21:16.008 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
LIGO is so sensitive, it
actually measures
the compressing and stretching
of space itself.

21:16.041 --> 21:19.178 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It is the most precise measuring
device ever
built.

21:19.211 --> 21:25.718 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It can detect a disturbance of
-- now, listen
to this -- one part in 1,000
billion billion,

21:25.751 --> 21:30.256 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
or something like 1/1,000 of the
diameter
of a proton.

21:30.289 --> 21:32.491 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
That is hard to -- it's
mind-boggling.

21:32.525 --> 21:33.492 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
All right?

21:33.526 --> 21:35.294 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We're deep in the quantum world
here.

21:35.327 --> 21:37.863 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right, we
don't talk
about math that much, but what
about the math

21:37.897 --> 21:38.864 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
prize?

21:38.898 --> 21:40.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MILES O'BRIEN: Yes.

21:40.799 --> 21:44.303 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I know folks might have some
flashbacks to
middle school right now, but
this is interesting.

21:44.336 --> 21:50.042 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Jean Bourgain of Princeton was
awarded for
contributions to
high-dimensional geometry

21:50.075 --> 21:51.877 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and some other branches of that.

21:51.911 --> 21:55.915 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, his main innovation was
expanding the
Fourier analysis, which I know
you know well,

21:55.948 --> 21:57.716 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Hari.

21:57.750 --> 22:02.655 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's a method to break down
messy signals
into basic repeated components
like a sine

22:02.688 --> 22:05.257 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
or cosine graph you might
remember from high
school.

22:05.291 --> 22:10.462 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, this makes it easier to
understand the
underlying structures of complex
mathematical

22:10.496 --> 22:13.532 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
situations, both physical and
theoretical.

22:13.566 --> 22:16.402 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think we better to end it
there, because
it's going to get deep very
quickly.

22:16.435 --> 22:19.271 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: I remember the
tension in
my geometry classes were whether
or not you

22:19.305 --> 22:21.106 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
should have those Texas
Instruments calculators.

22:21.140 --> 22:22.174 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Oh, it's cheating.

22:22.208 --> 22:24.176 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You should do these sine graphs
yourselves.

22:24.210 --> 22:29.215 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, speaking of life back in
the old days,
there are also prizes for
younger scientists.

22:29.248 --> 22:30.449 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What were they getting prizes
for?

22:30.482 --> 22:31.450 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MILES O'BRIEN: Yes.

22:31.483 --> 22:33.219 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And this is exciting stuff.

22:33.252 --> 22:39.024 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Two high school students, Deanna
See from
Singapore and Antonella Masini
from Peru,

22:39.058 --> 22:41.660 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
