23:54.667 --> 23:59.905 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and a historic recording from
the day that
lived in infamy.

23:59.938 --> 24:05.411 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But first: a pioneer in the
traditionally
male-dominated world of
sportswriting.

24:05.444 --> 24:09.081 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Claire Smith has been covering
baseball for
more than four decades.

24:09.114 --> 24:14.320 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
She was the first
African-American female
reporter to cover the game for a
newspaper.

24:14.353 --> 24:19.191 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Working for The New York Times,
The Philadelphia
Inquirer, and The Hartford
Courant during

24:19.224 --> 24:20.225 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
her career.

24:20.259 --> 24:21.660 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
She's now with ESPN.

24:21.694 --> 24:26.699 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, yesterday, she was awarded
the top honor
for a baseball writer.

24:26.732 --> 24:32.037 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Smith is the first woman to get
that prize
from the Baseball Writers
Association of America.

24:32.071 --> 24:37.142 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And she joins me now from
covering baseball's
winter meetings in Oxon Hill,
Maryland, where

24:37.176 --> 24:40.846 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
off-season trades and other
business is being
discussed.

24:40.879 --> 24:43.148 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Claire Smith, congratulations.

24:43.182 --> 24:44.717 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And what does this mean to you?

24:44.750 --> 24:48.120 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CLAIRE SMITH, Sportswriter,
ESPN: It means
the world.

24:48.153 --> 24:54.226 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I look around this hotel lobby,
I see my peers
out there hard at work.

24:54.259 --> 24:59.765 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I see so many that I watched
grow up in the
industry, so many that I have
worked with

24:59.798 --> 25:01.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
for three-plus decades.

25:01.533 --> 25:05.471 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And I -- they chose me.

25:05.504 --> 25:13.245 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They chose me to be the 68th
winner of this
award.

25:13.278 --> 25:20.219 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And previous winners were named
Grantland
Rice, Damon Runyon, Red Smith,
Wendell Smith,

25:20.252 --> 25:22.054 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Sam Lacy.

25:22.087 --> 25:31.196 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they said, you are the 68th
winner, the
first female, the first
African-American female.

25:31.230 --> 25:32.631 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's so humbling.

25:32.664 --> 25:33.832 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I'm overwhelmed.

25:33.866 --> 25:34.967 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I really am.

25:35.000 --> 25:37.169 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Why baseball?

25:37.202 --> 25:39.705 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Why did you want to write about
and cover
baseball?

25:39.738 --> 25:43.909 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
CLAIRE SMITH: Two words: Jackie
Robinson.

25:43.942 --> 25:47.079 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I was a child when my mother
told me that
story.

25:47.112 --> 25:53.919 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And in those two words, I
thought, this is
a great country.

25:53.952 --> 25:55.654 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Anything is possible.

25:55.687 --> 26:03.195 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And within this sport, this
sport taught this
country how to grow up and move
on.

26:03.228 --> 26:09.001 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It integrated 20-some years
before the United
States of America.

26:09.034 --> 26:16.008 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I was in elementary school when
the nuns at
Saint James took a third-grade
class down

26:16.041 --> 26:23.449 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to the church in the basement of
that Elkins
Park, Pennsylvania, school, and
showed us

26:23.482 --> 26:25.317 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
"The Jackie Robinson Story."

26:25.350 --> 26:34.793 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And Ruby Dee as Mrs. Rachel
Robinson, and
Jackie Robinson as Jackie
Robinson, they took

26:34.827 --> 26:36.128 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
my breath away.

26:36.161 --> 26:41.834 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They reminded me of my parents,
young and
proud.

26:41.867 --> 26:51.210 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I wanted to know more about
this couple
and that game and that man named
Branch Rickey.

26:51.243 --> 26:52.978 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I loved storytelling.

26:53.011 --> 27:01.320 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
My parents bought me an old
Olympia typewriter
and gave me paper as a child, a
preteen.

27:01.353 --> 27:03.822 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I loved pecking on that.

27:03.856 --> 27:10.529 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But that story captured my
imagination, and
I still wear Jackie's number a
lot.

27:10.562 --> 27:17.069 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I loved the idea of baseball and
what it did
for this country, what Jackie
and the Dodgers

27:17.102 --> 27:18.070 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
did.

27:18.103 --> 27:20.005 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: It is so
inspiring.

27:20.038 --> 27:26.545 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But once you got into writing
about and covering
baseball, as a woman, you found
out it wasn't

27:26.578 --> 27:30.015 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
as easy as maybe you might have
thought going
in?

27:30.048 --> 27:32.484 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
I mean, I'm particularly
interested in what
happened in 1984.

27:32.518 --> 27:41.593 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CLAIRE SMITH: Well, Judy, I had
a long career
with one bad day.

27:41.627 --> 27:49.268 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that was in 1984 in the
postseason, Padres
at Cubs, a playoff game.

27:49.301 --> 27:55.774 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I was pushed out, physically
pushed out
of the clubhouse because the
Padres didn't

27:55.807 --> 28:01.980 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
adhere to the National League's
edict that
the National League controlled
the clubhouses

28:02.014 --> 28:04.449 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
once the postseason started.

28:04.483 --> 28:14.493 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I had so many people jump to my
defense, not
necessarily the Padres club, but
Padres player,

28:14.526 --> 28:20.599 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
