his family.

39:49.587 --> 39:53.191 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I don't know how newsworthy that
was, but
people have made the point that
we had the

39:53.224 --> 39:57.195 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
9/11 attacks, people needed to
know where
President Bush was.

39:57.228 --> 40:02.100 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
President Reagan, sadly, there
was an assassination
attempt, and the pool needed to
know what

40:02.133 --> 40:04.235 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
was going on with that, and on
and on.

40:04.269 --> 40:09.407 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So we have certainly had
instances in our
history where unexpected events
happened,

40:09.440 --> 40:15.246 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and a group of reporters,
broadcast, print,
now digital, photographers
needed to be there.

40:15.280 --> 40:17.448 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So the pool is important.

40:17.482 --> 40:22.754 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I think we're seeing that
Mr. Trump is
either not aware of traditions
or has his

40:22.787 --> 40:24.689 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
own opinion about them.

40:24.722 --> 40:27.125 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right,
Micheline Maynard,
I'm sure we will have more
conversations about

40:27.158 --> 40:28.126 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
this in the future.

40:28.159 --> 40:30.695 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Thanks so much.

40:30.728 --> 40:40.438 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MICHELINE MAYNARD: Thank you for
having me.

40:40.471 --> 40:47.912 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: In the charged
atmosphere at
this time around the role of
Muslims in America

40:47.945 --> 40:53.751 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
comes what is billed as the
first major exhibition
on in the United States on the
Qur'an.

40:53.785 --> 40:55.486 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Jeffrey Brown reports.

40:55.520 --> 40:56.688 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MASSUMEH FARHAD, Chief Curator,
Arthur M.
Sackler Gallery, Smithsonian
Institution:

40:56.721 --> 40:59.724 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
This is one of the great
highlights of the
exhibition.

40:59.757 --> 41:09.567 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's a Qur'an from the early
14th century,
from about 1330, signed by a
great master.

41:09.600 --> 41:10.568 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Signed?

41:10.601 --> 41:11.569 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MASSUMEH FARHAD: Signed.

41:11.602 --> 41:13.338 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes.

41:13.371 --> 41:18.343 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A holy book, as a work of art,
the Qur'an,
sacred to some 1.6 billion
Muslims around

41:18.376 --> 41:20.411 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the world.

41:20.445 --> 41:25.817 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
A new exhibition at the
Smithsonian Institution's
Sackler Gallery in Washington,
D.C., presents

41:25.850 --> 41:30.588 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
68 of the most important and
exquisite Qur'ans
ever produced.

41:30.621 --> 41:37.095 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Dating from the late 7th to
early 17 centuries,
they come from many parts of the
Islamic world

41:37.128 --> 41:42.834 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and are part of the collection
of the Museum
of Turkish and Islamic Arts in
Istanbul.

41:42.867 --> 41:46.437 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's where Sackler chief
curator Massumeh
Farhad first saw them.

41:46.471 --> 41:51.509 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MASSUMEH FARHAD: I realized that
these were
true works of art, that every
single one of

41:51.542 --> 41:59.484 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
them was astounding in its sort
of mastery
of calligraphy, of the styles,
and also of

41:59.517 --> 42:01.386 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the scale of the works.

42:01.419 --> 42:08.860 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that is something that, to
me, was very
important, and motivated me in
trying to organize

42:08.893 --> 42:16.401 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this exhibition, because I
thought it really
shifted my perception of what
these works

42:16.434 --> 42:18.169 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
are.

42:18.202 --> 42:21.239 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I'm hoping that it will also
shift the
perception of the visitors who
come to the

42:21.272 --> 42:23.107 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
museum to see the exhibition.

42:23.141 --> 42:28.346 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: For Muslims, the
Qur'an is
a divine text, a series of
revelations transmitted

42:28.379 --> 42:33.551 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
from the angel Gabriel to the
Prophet Mohammed
between 610 and 632.

42:33.584 --> 42:39.624 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It includes references to
earlier figures,
including Abraham, Moses and
Jesus.

42:39.657 --> 42:41.426 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
The term itself means
recitation.

42:41.459 --> 42:44.328 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The Qur'an stems from an oral
tradition.

42:44.362 --> 42:49.400 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the text was written down
and codified
in a fixed form not long after
the death of

42:49.434 --> 42:51.335 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Mohammed.

42:51.369 --> 42:55.740 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Maria Dakake teaches Islamic
religious thought
and history at George Mason
University.

42:55.773 --> 42:58.309 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARIA DAKAKE, George Mason
University: One
of the things that is rather
striking about

42:58.342 --> 43:03.714 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the Qur'an when people read it
for the first
time is that it often takes the
form of direct

43:03.748 --> 43:04.715 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
address.

43:04.749 --> 43:07.552 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, it will say sometimes, oh,
you who believe.

43:07.585 --> 43:11.856 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Sometimes, it will address all
human beings,
oh, humankind.

43:11.889 --> 43:17.695 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
It is a series of moral
exhortations, exhortations
to virtue.

43:17.728 --> 43:22.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It includes many stories of
prophets before
the time of Mohammed.

43:22.266 --> 43:27.238 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It is an attempt to grab the
listener, or
grab the reader, to wake them
up, to make

43:27.271 --> 43:31.275 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
them think about their life,
about the world
around them.

43:31.309 --> 43:36.347 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's a lot of passages with
rhetorical sentences,
right?

43:36.380 --> 43:38.449 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Did you not consider this?

43:38.483 --> 43:39.450 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Didn't you think about this?

43:39.484 --> 43:41.352 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
How did you get here?

43:41.385 --> 43:46.324 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The exhibition
includes furniture,
stands to hold manuscripts, and
chests to

43:46.357 --> 43:48.092 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
store them.

43:48.125 --> 43:52.663 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Many of these Qur'ans were
originally commissioned
and donated or collected by
rulers.

43:52.697 --> 43:58.402 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Early manuscripts, on parchment,
feature plain
ink and simple designs.

43:58.436 --> 44:05.109 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Later, artists and calligraphers
developed
ever more elaborate and ornate
script, illumination,

44:05.142 --> 44:10.081 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and geometric patterns, in light
of Islam's
proscription against figurative
images, to

44:10.114 --> 44:12.550 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
make each manuscript a singular
work.

44:12.583 --> 44:19.423 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MASSUMEH FARHAD: It's how they
sort of use
their individuality is really
quite remarkable.

44:19.457 --> 44:26.497 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the greater master, the
better they can
sort of manipulate the style
without breaking

44:26.531 --> 44:31.068 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the rules, because you could not
break the
rules of a particular style of
calligraphy,

44:31.102 --> 44:37.174 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but you could sort of stretch
them, and sort
of introduce your own sort of
touch to a particular

44:37.208 --> 44:40.645 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
style or a particular type of
writing.

44:40.678 --> 44:45.016 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Some of these
masters are well
known to scholars, like the
maker of this

44:45.049 --> 44:50.187 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Qur'an, Abdullah Sayrafi, who
spent most of
his life in Tabriz in
Northwestern Iran.

44:50.221 --> 44:56.994 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MASSUMEH FARHAD: What is
remarkable about
Abdullah Sayrafi is the fact
that he was able

44:57.028 --> 45:04.902 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to write in more than one style
of calligraphy,
because, usually, most
calligraphers specialized

45:04.936 --> 45:07.939 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in one style and one particular
size alone.

45:07.972 --> 45:11.375 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It was clearly a Qur'an that was
meant for
display.

45:11.409 --> 45:20.585 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It is so lavish in its use of
both illumination,
in terms of that very rich black
ink, the

45:20.618 --> 45:23.521 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
fact that every gold line is
outlined in black.

45:23.554 --> 45:30.261 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I mean, this is a visual feast,
and it's supposed
to be viewed and looked at.

45:30.294 --> 45:32.830 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, it was meant as a display
copy.

45:32.863 --> 45:35.299 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: How long would it
take to do
something like this?

45:35.333 --> 45:36.734 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MASSUMEH FARHAD: Many years.

45:36.767 --> 45:38.202 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Years for each
one?

45:38.235 --> 45:40.004 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MASSUMEH FARHAD: For each one.

45:40.037 --> 45:43.741 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Even amid a
highly contentious
and politicized atmosphere today
concerning

45:43.774 --> 45:49.013 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Muslims in America, the curators
say this
exhibition was long in the
works, and the

45:49.046 --> 45:51.349 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
timing is coincidental.

45:51.382 --> 45:56.587 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For her part, Maria Dakake hopes
it will shine
a different kind of spotlight on
Islam and

45:56.621 --> 45:58.122 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the Qur'an.

45:58.155 --> 46:00.758 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARIA DAKAKE: You will hear
sometimes Islamophobic
comments about Islam.

46:00.791 --> 46:05.162 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they will say, well, you
know, why would
I want to know anything about
this text?

46:05.196 --> 46:07.398 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I see what kinds of things it
produces, right?

46:07.431 --> 46:11.102 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It produces people who behave in
these violent
ways or something like that.

46:11.135 --> 46:15.606 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But when you come here, you see
the larger
reality of what it produced,
right?

46:15.640 --> 46:17.775 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It produced beauty.

46:17.808 --> 46:20.044 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It produced scientific inquiry.

46:20.077 --> 46:22.847 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It inspired literary endeavors.

46:22.880 --> 46:29.253 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And in a time of Islamophobia, I
think what's
so valuable about this
collection is to see

46:29.286 --> 46:34.659 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the kind of artistic elements,
the beauty
that the Qur'an really brought.

46:34.692 --> 46:40.831 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The Art of the
Qur'an is on
exhibition through February.

46:40.865 --> 46:51.409 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
From the Sackler Gallery in
Washington, D.C.,
I'm Jeffrey Brown for the "PBS
NewsHour."

46:51.442 --> 47:03.220 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now a perspective
on the benefits
of learning and speaking a
foreign language.

47:03.254 --> 47:07.725 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Lauren Collins is a
correspondent for "The
New Yorker" magazine, and she
brings us the

47:07.758 --> 47:12.930 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
latest installment in our series
IMHO: In
My Humble Opinion.

47:12.963 --> 47:18.636 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
LAUREN COLLINS, "The New
Yorker": (SPEAKING
FRENCH)

47:18.669 --> 47:23.140 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What I just said is that, five
years ago,
I didn't speak a word of French.

47:23.174 --> 47:24.475 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And why would I have?

47:24.508 --> 47:26.777 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I was born and raised in a small
town in North
Carolina.

47:26.811 --> 47:31.982 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In high school, I took Spanish,
and like a
lot of people who take high
school Spanish,

47:32.016 --> 47:36.053 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I failed to retain much more
than hola and
gracias and habla English?

47:36.087 --> 47:38.889 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I guess at the time, it didn't
seem all that
important.

47:38.923 --> 47:43.728 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I have come to believe that
learning a
foreign language is a quietly
revolutionary

47:43.761 --> 47:47.598 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
act and that there's never been
a better time
to do it.

47:47.631 --> 47:51.902 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
My French revolution started
when I met a
man named Olivier at a party.

47:51.936 --> 47:56.540 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Besides the fact that we were
both living
in London, we had exactly zero
in common,

47:56.574 --> 47:59.276 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
but somehow we got to talking
and neither
of us wanted to stop.

47:59.310 --> 48:04.715 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Olivier spoke beautiful English,
so it wasn't
a big deal that I didn't speak
his language.

48:04.749 --> 48:06.917 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But then things got serious, and
we got married.

48:06.951 --> 48:09.453 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I told his mother I had
given birth to
a coffee machine.

48:09.487 --> 48:14.158 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we moved to French-speaking
Switzerland,
and eventually it became clear
that I was

48:14.191 --> 48:16.694 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
going to have to learn French.

48:16.727 --> 48:18.829 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I signed up for an intensive
class.

48:18.863 --> 48:22.967 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
My fellow students came from all
over the
world, Germany, Argentina,
Japan.

48:23.000 --> 48:28.506 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The funny thing about French
classes, they're
the one place that, by
definition, you're

48:28.539 --> 48:31.776 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
never going to find someone who
speaks French.

48:31.809 --> 48:32.777 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
But I kept at it.

48:32.810 --> 48:34.044 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
We all did.

48:34.078 --> 48:37.815 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, very slowly, I found myself
getting the
hang of things.

48:37.848 --> 48:41.652 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One day, something clicked, and
I heard my
husband's voice for the first
time.

48:41.685 --> 48:45.956 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There are so many advantages to
learning a
language.

48:45.990 --> 48:48.425 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Being bilingual improves your
memory.

48:48.459 --> 48:52.863 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And several studies have
suggested that it
may even stave off Alzheimer's
and dementia.

48:52.897 --> 48:58.169 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, for me, most incredible
thing was being
all of a sudden privy to a
parallel world

48:58.202 --> 49:03.340 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I hadn't even known existed, a
world in which
there was a word for a person
who got cold

49:03.374 --> 49:08.179 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
easily, where a man's shirt was
feminine,
but a woman's shirt was
masculine, where there

49:08.212 --> 49:10.781 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
wasn't just one past tense, but
two.

49:10.815 --> 49:16.520 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Each time, I had to decide
whether a person
was a vous or a tu, an
acquaintance or an

49:16.554 --> 49:19.757 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
intimate, which is to say
basically every
time I encountered someone.

49:19.790 --> 49:25.996 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I felt my boundaries shifting,
my relationships
being recategorized into public
and private.

49:26.030 --> 49:30.901 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What if, in this moment of
rising intolerance,
nationalism and xenophobia, we
could all put

49:30.935 --> 49:33.737 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ourselves in another person's
tongue?

49:33.771 --> 49:38.275 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
When you learn a language, you
benefit not
only yourself, but also society.

49:38.309 --> 49:43.547 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Botching conjugations and
brandishing your
ridiculous accent, you develop
empathy.

49:43.581 --> 49:51.121 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You start to see that the world
looks different,
depending on where you stand and
what you

49:51.155 --> 49:54.258 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
speak.

49:54.291 --> 50:03.067 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Now to our
"NewsHour" Shares,
something that caught our eye,
that might

50:03.100 --> 50:05.069 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
be of interest to you, too.

50:05.102 --> 50:10.140 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As we noted earlier, today marks
the 75th
anniversary of Japan's surprise
attack on

50:10.174 --> 50:12.142 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Pearl Harbor.

50:12.176 --> 50:15.980 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The ensuing battle claimed the
lives of more
than 2,400 Americans, and
triggered U.S. involvement

50:16.013 --> 50:17.781 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in World War II.

50:17.815 --> 50:23.153 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
An unknown NBC reporter in
Honolulu spoke
by telephone that day in a
dispatch that was

50:23.187 --> 50:25.756 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
broadcast live across the
nation.

50:25.789 --> 50:26.757 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Here's an excerpt:

50:26.790 --> 50:27.758 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
REPORTER: One, two, three, four.

